layed the fiddle, surely, in the way lackadaisical footmen in Russia used to twang guitars on summer evenings, was called a “musician,” which at once turned me into a musician too. Later in the day, at a small border town, I purchased a suitcase, an overcoat, and so forth, upon which both bag and gun were discarded—no, I will not say what I did with them: be silent, Rhenish waters! And presently, a very unshaven gentleman in a cheap black overcoat was on the safer side of the frontier and 